Yes, I know MS does not like this nor supports it but...I would like to do so.

In user mode my code works fine, but when running as a windows service the following line of code returns null. How determine the error that causing it to return as null?

Word.Document newDocument = wordApplication.Documents.Open(tempFile);

I am hoping to load up a document and use this to convert it to text for downstream parsing. But this returns null. No exception. And I cannot find any errors in the event log.

[Update] I put the debug console on and it says "Failed to Resolve Assembly" but I have noticed that in the user mode and it does not seem to stop it.

this means newDocument is null? which assembly failed to resolve?
can i see the complete console log?

 Attempt has been made to use a COM object that does not have a backing class factory.
I just tried that morning to see if I get closer to what is going on. The logs from above are from an App Domain implementation.

" Attempt has been made to use a COM object that does not have a backing class factory."
this message means the original memory instance(in word application memoryi) behind the com proxy is dead. not sure why...
i want add the beta release NetOffice 1.6.1 in this week and create a concept test "use NetOffice in system service"
you can help me and send a me a simplified project(remove private code) to analyze the problem to: public[dot]sebastian[at]web.de
i want help you as fast as possible before i create a new release.
i see also the current debugconsole is not very helpful. sorry is a very old feature. as i start with netoffice this output was helpful for me but i see its not for each other. NO 1.6.1 includes much more options for diagnostics. :) (external console observer, ipc debug channels and many more)
